## Free-play Results (self-play 8v0)

### 5000 steps
- TV142 baseline: 6.67
- TV157 (aggressive 6a): 6.33 (-5%)
- TV158 (carbon + aggressive 6a): 5.85 (-12%)
- TV156-code (carbon mining): 4.04 (-39%)

### 2000 steps (5 runs, statistical)
- TV142: avg 1.94 (2.05, 2.08, 1.91, 1.98, 1.70)
- TV162 (lower 6a thresholds): avg 1.85 (2.16, 2.26, 1.13) — closest to TV142!
- TV159 (30% stag scramble): avg 1.61 (2.64, 0.00, 2.19) — extreme variance
- TV163 (adaptive scramble): avg 1.61 (1.69, 1.69, 1.22, 1.75, 1.70) — 17% worse

### Conclusions
- Carbon mining HURTS — silicon becomes bottleneck when carbon over-prioritized
- Adaptive scramble hurts — world model remembers distant junctions → 100% scramble
- TV162 matches TV142 in self-play — worth tournament comparison
- 0.00 wipeout games are random map effects, not policy bugs

## Key Learnings
1. 50% stagnation scramble (TV142) is the single most important feature
2. Aggressive 4a (step 50, no economy gate) is a real improvement
3. Balanced 6a (4 aligners from step 30) is a real improvement
4. Self-play predictions have ~50% tournament correlation
5. Tournament scores normalize significantly after 50+ matches
6. Early leaderboard positions (< 20 matches) are very volatile
7. TV142's conservative 6a economy ramp is CRITICAL to its #1 ranking
   - TV154 (aggressive 6a + 50% stag) = #2 at 13.76, 0.54 behind TV142
   - Aggressive 6a depletes resources faster → aligners stall on hearts
8. **FORCED exploration in stagnation is essential** (TV163 insight)
   - Adaptive scramble (scramble when targets visible) → nearly 100% scramble
   - World model remembers enemy junctions even far away
   - step%200<100 FORCES exploration even when scramble targets known
   - This prevents agents from burning all hearts on scrambling
9. Carbon-weighted mining hurts — silicon bottleneck emerges when carbon over-prioritized
   - Existing resource_priority (sort by lowest inventory) is already adaptive and optimal
10. Self-play variance is HIGH — need 5+ runs to get reliable signal

